<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What does FLAMES stand for?", answer: "FLAMES stands for Friends, Love, Affection, Marriage, Enemies, and Siblings — the six possible outcomes of the classic schoolyard relationship game. Each letter represents a relationship type, and the math of the game eliminates letters one by one until only one remains. The remaining letter is the 'verdict' for the two names you entered." },
  { question: "How do you play FLAMES?", answer: "Write both names down. Cross out the letters they share (one for one). Count how many letters remain in total. Then go around the word FLAMES, counting each letter and removing the letter you land on at that count, then start counting from the next letter — repeat until only one letter is left. That letter is your result. The calculator does all of this automatically." },
  { question: "Where did FLAMES come from?", answer: "FLAMES has been a popular schoolyard pastime in India, the UK, the US, and many English-speaking countries since at least the 1970s. It evolved from earlier paper-and-pencil love games like MASH (Mansion, Apartment, Shack, House) and 'He loves me, he loves me not'. No one is sure who invented it, but it spread through schools by word of mouth long before the internet, and it survives in digital form because the math is simple and the result feels personal." },
  { question: "Is FLAMES accurate?", answer: "Not even slightly. It's a deterministic word game — the same two names always produce the same result, which means there's no real prediction happening. It's a fun way to break the ice, prompt a giggle in a group chat, or pretend the universe has decided your fate. Don't break up with anyone over a FLAMES result, and don't propose to anyone because of one either." },
  { question: "Can FLAMES give the same answer for everyone?", answer: "No. The result depends on the exact letters in both names. Tiny changes (full name vs nickname, with or without middle name) often produce different outcomes, which is why the game feels personal. Try variations of your names — Mike and Michael will land on different results, as will using last names or not. The variability is part of the fun." }
]) %>

